liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A third convoy of aid trucks has entered Gaza through the Rafah crossing from Egypt, Reuters reports. The news agency cited an aid worker and two security sources. The Associated Press also reports that a "small aid shipment" has been allowed in. Here's a map showing the Rafah crossing, the only one way into Gaza that is not controlled by Israel. On Saturday, 20 trucks entered Gaza in the first aid shipment into the territory since Israel imposed a complete siege at the start of the war. Israel allowed a second convoy of 15 trucks into Gaza on Sunday .

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Israeli military says it has confirmed that 222 people are being held as captives in Gaza. Chief military spokesperson Rear Admiral Daniel Hagari confirmed the number in a televised briefing. Israeli ground forces also conducted limited raids into Gaza overnight to fight gunmen, Hagari said.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israel hit Gaza overnight with "almost non-stop" air strikes, ABC Middle East correspondent Allyson Horn reports from Netivot, southern Israel, roughly 10 kilometres from the Gaza border. “We’ve been feeling reverberations all the way into southern Israel where we’re located. You can feel the sonic booms physically as those rockets are being dropped into Gaza.” The number of rockets coming from Hamas however, has significantly decreased with nothing coming in for the last 12 hours and less than 5 sent in the 12 hours prior. "It seems to suggest that Hamas might now be taking stock of its weaponry and perhaps preserving some of that weaponry for the next phase of this war." There is also growing concern that Iran may join the conflict. Iran’s Foreign Ministry has said all options are on the table and has warned that the situation could spiral out of control if Israel doesn’t stop its siege on Gaza.
